Histogram of Users’ Birthdays

Notes: The histogram can be created using qplot or the ggplot library. Each has different syntax. The histogram is being made of the date of birth day for each user.

qplot syntax: qplot(x=dob_day, data=pf)

ggplot2 syntax: ggplot(aes(x=dob_day), data = pf) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:31)

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(aes(x=dob_day), data=pf) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:31)

What are some things that you notice about this histogram?

Response: Many more people have birthdays on the first day of the month than any other day. ***

Perceived Audience Size

Faceting

Notes: facet wrap is an additional formula to qplot or ggpot that that takes a formula. The syntax is facet_wrap(~variable). This create a histogram for each variable in the facet wrap formula brackets.

Facet grid is similar to facet wrap except it spreads out the histograms over two variables. The syntax is facet_grid(vertical~horizontal).

ggplot(aes(x=dob_day), data=pf) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=1) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:31) +
  facet_wrap(~dob_month)

Let’s take another look at our plot. What stands out to you here?

Response: There are a lot more birthdays on January 1 than any other day of the year. ***

Be Skeptical - Outliers and Anomalies

Notes: Outliers and anomalies represent that there may limitations to the data or something wrong with the data collection. Sometimes data sets are top coded which means that values above a certain threshold are censored or replaced with a random value to protect identity.

Outliers can fall into a few categories: * Good data about an extreme case * Bad data about an extreme case * Bad data about a not extreme case ***

Moira’s Outlier

Notes: #### Which case do you think applies to Moira’s outlier? Response: Moira’s outlier was bad data about an extreme case since the respondent said that 10 million people saw his/her post when that large of a number is not possible with the number of friends allowed on Facebook. ***

Omitting NA Values

Notes: NA can be omitted by subsetting the data and using !is.na(column) syntax. All of the data will be included except for the NA in the specific column.

ggplot(aes(x=friend_count), data=subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=25) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,1000), breaks = seq(0,1000,50)) +
  facet_wrap(~gender)

Tenure

Notes: Let’s measure the tenure, the amount of time that a user has been a member of Facebook. The binwidth will be set to show the number of days.

This time we will add color to the histogram by using: geom_histogram(color=“black”, fill = “blue”)

ggplot(aes(x=tenure), data = pf) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=30, color = 'black', fill = 'blue') +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:2000)
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

How would you create a histogram of tenure by year?

ggplot(aes(tenure/365), data = pf) +

Transforming Data

Notes: Sometimes data is better represented on a log scale or a square root scale. This is especially the case when there are large outliers or the peaks are much larger than the majority of the data.

Data can be transformed in this way in summary statement or plot using the log10, sqrt, or any other scaling factor command.

summary(log10(pf$tenure))

scale_x_log10() for plots

grid.arrange() to show multiple plots on the same canvas.

library(gridExtra)
p1 = ggplot(aes(x=friend_count), data=pf) +
  geom_histogram(color='black', fill = 'green')
p2 = p1 + scale_x_log10()
p3 = p1 + scale_x_sqrt()

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol=1)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Add a Scaling Layer

Notes: Adding a scaling layer, like that done in ggplot, keeps the actual numbers instead of the logarithmic numbers. It’s more intuitive.

q1 = ggplot(data = pf, aes(x=log10(friend_count))) +
  geom_histogram(color='black')

q2 = ggplot(data=pf, aes(x=friend_count)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  geom_histogram(color='black')

grid.arrange(q1, q2)

Frequency Polygons

Notes: Frequency polygons are like histograms except they connect the top of the histogram only and come out as line graphs.

The code to make frequency polygons is to add geom_freqpoly(aes())

Below are frequency polygons of the friend count percentage of both genders as well as which gender gets more likes.

ggplot(aes(x=friend_count, y=..count../sum(..count..)), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color=gender), binwidth=50) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,1000), breaks = seq(0,1000, 50)) +
  xlab('Number of Freinds') +
  ylab('Percentage of Total Users')
## Warning: Removed 2949 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

ggplot(aes(x=www_likes), data=subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color=gender)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  xlab('Number of Likes made on the Internet') +

Box Plots

Notes: Box plots are good visualization tool for outliers and data within the interquartile range (IQR)

Box plots are created using the geom_boxplot() syntax.

ggplot(aes(x=gender, y=friend_count), data=subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_boxplot()

Adjust the code to focus on users who have friend counts between 0 and 1000.

ggplot(aes(x=gender, y=friend_count), data=subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,1000))

The data can be limited and still take the excluded points into the calculation by using coord_cartesian(ylim=c())

Box Plots, Quartiles, and Friendships

Notes: The box plot is interpreted in the following way:

  • The bold line in the middle is the median value of the data and the top and bottom line are the 3rd and 1st quartile, respectively.

Getting Logical

Notes: It is often useful to have logical expressions when tryin to determine the effectiveness of something. In this case, we will find out how many users use mobiles to check Facebook.

pf$mobile_check <- NA

pf$mobile_check <- ifelse(pf$mobile_likes > 0, 1, 0)
pf$mobile_check <- factor(pf$mobile_check)

summary(pf$mobile_check)/length(pf$mobile_check)
##         0         1 
## 0.3540903 0.6459097

Analyzing One Variable

Reflection: Making histograms, frequency polygons, and box plots to visualize a large dataset can be very helpful in doing EDA.

We should also explore a new dataset by looking at it’s basic statistics: str(dataset) summary(dataset) row.names(dataset) nrow(dataset) ncol(dataset) names(dataset)

Look at the individual variables in the dataset to see what information is available.
